This is a known breaking change. Android 15 (API 35) enforces **edge-to-edge** rendering and ignores `SOFT_INPUT_ADJUST_RESIZE`. You need to react to **IME window insets** instead.

**In `Platforms/Android/MainActivity.cs`:**

```csharp
using Android.OS;
using AndroidX.Core.View;

[Activity(/* existing attributes — remove any WindowSoftInputMode here */)]
public class MainActivity : MauiAppCompatActivity
{
    protected override void OnCreate(Bundle? savedInstanceState)
    {
        base.OnCreate(savedInstanceState);

        if (Window?.DecorView?.RootView is Android.Views.View root)
        {
            ViewCompat.SetOnApplyWindowInsetsListener(root, new ImeInsetsListener());
        }
    }

    private class ImeInsetsListener : Java.Lang.Object, IOnApplyWindowInsetsListener
    {
        public WindowInsetsCompat OnApplyWindowInsets(
            Android.Views.View v, WindowInsetsCompat insets)
        {
            var ime    = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.Ime());
            var bars   = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.SystemBars());
            int bottom = Math.Max(ime.Bottom, bars.Bottom);

            v.SetPadding(v.PaddingLeft, v.PaddingTop, v.PaddingRight, bottom);
            return insets;
        }
    }
}
```

**Why this works:**

| .NET 9 (API ≤ 34) | .NET 10 (API 35+) |
|---|---|
| `AdjustResize` shrinks the window | Ignored — window is always full-screen |
| System handles layout shift | **You** respond to `Ime()` insets |

**Key points:**

1. **Remove** any `WindowSoftInputMode = SoftInput.AdjustResize` from your `[Activity]` attribute.
2. The listener fires whenever the keyboard opens/closes, giving you the keyboard height via `ime.Bottom`.
3. `Math.Max(ime, systemBars)` ensures the content stays above the nav bar when the keyboard is closed.
4. Your XAML needs no changes — the platform root view's padding pushes everything up.

If you also need to **scroll your message list**, add this to your `CollectionView`/`ListView` page:

```csharp
#if ANDROID
Microsoft.Maui.ApplicationModel.Platform.CurrentActivity?
    .Window?.SetSoftInputMode(Android.Views.SoftInput.AdjustNothing);
#endif
```

…so the insets listener has full control, then scroll programmatically in response to keyboard appearance if needed.
